# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cyrillic-alphabets
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] Louis Braille's original publication, *Procedure for Writing Words, Music, and Plainsong in Dots* (1829), credits Barbier's night writing as being the basis for the braille script.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] It differed in a fundamental way from modern braille: It contained nine decades (series) of characters rather than the modern five, utilizing dashes as well as dots.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] Braille recognized, however, that the dashes were problematic, being difficult to distinguish from the dots in practice, and those characters were abandoned in the second edition of the book.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] The first four decades indicated the 40 letters of the alphabet (39 letters of the French alphabet, plus English *w*); the fifth the digits; the sixth punctuation; and the seventh and part of the eighth mathematical symbols.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] The seventh decade was also used for musical notes.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] Most of the remaining characters were unassigned.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] Thus the 1st and 5th decades occupied only the top half of the cell, while all characters in the other decades had a dot or dash in the bottom row.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] The supplemental signs were ⠄⠤⠜⠼ and a top dash with ⠠⠰.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] Of the 125 (53) possible patterns, 97 were used.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] The modern 5th decade and other supplemental signs do not appear in the 1829 version of braille, apart from ⠐ and ⠒ in plainsong notation.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] Anticipating that the dashes might prove problematic, Braille provided that the supplemental sign ⠼ (now known as the number sign) would shift the decade by four.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] That is, adding it to the first four decades would produce substitutes for the fifth through eighth.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] Only its use to replace the old fifth decade has been retained; the old sixth decade survives as the modern fifth, with the dash removed and the dots shifted down to replace it.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] The book allots a great deal of space to the representation of music.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] Instrumental notation was largely a one-to-one transcription of the system already in use for the blind.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] The durations of the notes and the accidentals, however, had to be replaced; for these the 7th decade was used, as shown in the table above.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] A simplified system for plainsong was provided.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] The twelve notes are the twelve characters of the upper half of the cell (the first and fifth decades) which do not have dashes.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] By themselves (1st decade), they indicate half notes.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] Quarter notes are 2nd decade, dotted quarter notes 3rd, and eighth notes 4th.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] Dotted half notes are indicated by a dash below (6th decade), whole notes by a dash above (7th decade), and dotted whole notes by a mid dash (8th decade).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] The alto, bass, treble, and tenor clefs were indicated by the 5th–8th characters of the fifth decade. ⠐ is the sharp-note prefix, ⠒ the bass-note prefix, and the equivalent with a dash the natural prefix. ⠄⠤ are the repetition sign and 'star'.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] The book finishes with a proposal for braille shorthand, utilizing the first decade for vowels, and the fifth for consonants (without a voicing distinction).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] That is, Braille's shorthand used a 4-dot cell rather than the standard 6-dot cell, taking two-thirds the space of normal braille, and one-third the space of Barbier's night writing.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] In the classroom, Braille's students found the characters with dashes to be impractical, as the dashes were not easily distinguishable from pairs of dots, and they were quickly abandoned.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] The second edition of the *Procédé*, published in 1837, sets out French Braille essentially as we know it today.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] According to Henri (1952), at right, the numerical sign was used with the new fifth decade, plus one of the supplementary characters, for mathematical notation: ⠼⠖ +, ⠼⠤ −, ⠼⠦ ×, ⠼⠲ /, ⠼⠶ =, ⠼⠜ √.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] Several of these values continue today in Antoine notation.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] The official Unicode encoding for Braille only specifies codepoints for modern dot-only patterns.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] An unofficial encoding for dash patterns can be found in the Under-ConScript Unicode Registry, and as such may be found in some fonts that cover characters from that agreement.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1829-braille] Together, these two blocks can represent all cell definitions from the 1829 Braille specification.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1924-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The **1924 Constitution of the Soviet Union** was the communist state constitution adopted on 31 January 1924.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1924-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1924 Constitution was the first constitution of the Soviet Union and ratified by the Second Congress of Soviets.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1924-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] In essence, the 1924 Constitution was an expansion and generalization of the 1922 Treaty, with most of the major parts already specified by the treaty, and also allowed for a potential expansion of the Soviet Union.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1924-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Whereas the original Treaty had only 26 articles, the 1924 Constitution now had 72 divided into eleven chapters.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1924-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1924 Constitution replaced the Russian Constitution of 1918 which served as a precursor and influenced the main principles of the Union-wide constitution.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1924-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1924 Constitution established the Congress of Soviets to be the supreme body of Soviet state authority, with the Central Executive Committee having this authority during the interims and serving as the country's collective presidency.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1924-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The Central Executive Committee also elected the Council of People's Commissars, which served as the executive branch of the government.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1924-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The Central Executive Committee, effectively the legislature, was divided into the Soviet of the Union representing the constituent republics, and the Soviet of Nationalities representing directly the interests of nationality groups.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1924-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The Presidium supervised the government administration between sessions of the Central Executive Committee.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1924-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1924 Constitution survived six editions until it was replaced by the 1936 Constitution of the Soviet Union on 5 December 1936.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The **1936 Constitution of the Soviet Union**, also known as the **Stalin Constitution**, was the communist state constitution of the USSR adopted on 5 December 1936.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1936 Constitution was the second constitution of the Soviet Union and replaced the 1924 Constitution, with 5 December being celebrated annually as Soviet Constitution Day from its adoption by the Congress of Soviets.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] This date was considered the "second foundational moment" of the USSR, after the October Revolution in 1917.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1936 Constitution redesigned the government of the Soviet Union, expanded all manner of rights and freedoms, and spelled out a number of democratic procedures.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The Congress of Soviets replaced itself with the Supreme Soviet, which amended the 1936 Constitution in 1944.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1936 Constitution was the longest surviving constitution of the Soviet Union, and many Eastern Bloc countries later adopted constitutions that were closely modeled on it.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] It was replaced by the 1977 Constitution of the Soviet Union ("Brezhnev Constitution") on 7 October 1977.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1936 Constitution repealed restrictions on voting, abolishing the *lishentsy* category of people, and added universal direct suffrage and the right to work to rights guaranteed by the previous constitution.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] In addition, the 1936 Constitution recognized collective social and economic rights including the rights to work, rest and leisure, health protection, care in old age and sickness, housing, education and cultural benefits.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1936 Constitution also provided for the direct election of all government bodies and their reorganization into a single, uniform system.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Article 124 of the constitution guaranteed freedom of religion, including separation of (1) church and state, and (2) school from church.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The reasoning of the Article 124 is framed in terms of ensuring "to citizens freedom of conscience ...
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Freedom of religious worship and freedom of anti-religious propaganda is recognized for all citizens." Stalin included Article 124 in the face of stiff opposition, and it eventually led to rapprochement with the Russian Orthodox Church before and during World War 2.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The new constitution re-enfranchised certain religious people who had been specifically disenfranchised under the previous constitution.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The article resulted in members of the Russian Orthodox Church petitioning to reopen closed churches, gain access to jobs that had been closed to them as religious figures, and the attempt to run religious candidates in the 1937 elections.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Article 125 of the constitution guaranteed freedom of speech of the press and freedom of assembly.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1936 constitution specifically mentioned the role of the ruling All-Union Communist Party (Bolsheviks) for the first time.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Article 126 stated that the Party was the "vanguard of the working people in their struggle to strengthen and develop the socialist system and representing the leading core of all organizations of the working people, both public and state".
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] This provision was used to justify banning all other parties from functioning in the Soviet Union and legalizing the one-party state.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1936 Constitution replaced the Congress of Soviets of the Soviet Union with the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Unlike its unicameral predecessor, the Supreme Soviet contained two chambers: the Soviet of the Union and the Soviet of Nationalities.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The constitution empowered the Supreme Soviet to elect commissars, which performed most of the Supreme Soviet's work.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The Central Executive Committee of the Congress of Soviets was replaced by the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet which, much like its predecessor, exercised the full powers of the Supreme Soviet between sessions and had the right to interpret laws.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The Chairman of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet became the titular head of state of the Soviet Union.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The Council of People's Commissars, known after 1946 as the Council of Ministers, continued to act as the executive arm of the government.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1936 Constitution changed the names of all Union Republics, the constituent states of the Soviet Union, transposing the second word "socialist" and third word "soviet" (or equivalent e.g.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Republics were named after the primary nationality and followed by "Soviet Socialist Republic" (SSR), except for the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic (RSFSR).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1936 Constitution was written by a special commission of 31 members which General Secretary Joseph Stalin chaired.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Those who participated included (among others) Andrey Vyshinsky, Andrei Zhdanov, Maxim Litvinov, Kliment Voroshilov, Vyacheslav Molotov, Lazar Kaganovich, Nikolai Bukharin, and Karl Radek, though the latter two had less active input.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1936 Constitution enumerated economic rights not included in constitutions in the Western democracies.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The constitution was presented as a personal triumph for Stalin, who on this occasion was described by *Pravda* as "genius of the new world, the wisest man of the epoch, the great leader of communism".
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Arch Getty, "Many who lauded Stalin's Soviet Union as the most democratic country on earth lived to regret their words.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] After all, the Soviet Constitution of 1936 was adopted on the eve of the Great Terror of the late 1930s; the "thoroughly democratic" elections to the first Supreme Soviet permitted only uncontested candidates and took place at the height of the savage violence in 1937.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1944 amendments to the 1936 Constitution established separate branches of the Red Army for each Soviet Republic, and also established Republic-level commissariats for foreign affairs and defense, allowing them to be recognized as sovereign states in international law.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] This allowed for two Soviet Republics, Ukraine and Byelorussia, to join the United Nations General Assembly as founding members in 1945.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Some historical figures have seen the constitution as a propaganda document.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1936-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Isaac Deutscher called it "a veil of liberal phrases and premises over the guillotine in the background".
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The **1957 Economic Reform in the Soviet Union** (Russian: Экономическая реформа 1957 года в СССР) was a reform of national economic management carried out in 1957–1965.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] It was characterized by the replacement of the centralized sectoral management system, which had been used since the mid-1930s, with a decentralized, territorially distributed system, which in Soviet literature was called the "territorial principle management system".
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] It is associated with First Secretary of the Central Committee of the CPSU and (since 1958) Chairman of the Council of Ministers of the Soviet Union, Nikita Khrushchev.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] According to the initiators of the reform, decentralization of the production management system would increase its growth, improve product quality, optimize resource distribution, reduce equipment repair costs, and improve the organization of material and technical supplies.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] An attempt to rectify the situation by consolidating economic councils and merging administrative economic regions led to the emergence of intermediate levels of management in the form of republican and union councils of the national economy and sectoral state committees.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Research, design, and engineering organizations that were under the jurisdiction of sectoral management bodies were cut off from industrial enterprises, which continued to be subordinate to territorial bodies.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] This led to a decrease in the quality of design, construction and reconstruction of enterprises, slowed down the introduction of new technologies, machines and equipment and, as a result, led to a decrease in the quality of industrial products.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Nevertheless, this reform led to significant economic growth.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The problems of the Soviet economy continued to worsen, and by 1965 the trend towards centralization prevailed.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] After the death of Joseph Stalin in 1953, the leaders of the country and the party took a course on developing socially oriented sectors of the economy - construction, agriculture, light industry and production of consumer goods.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] However, by 1955, the course on the preferential development of consumer goods production was rejected in favour of the accelerated development of heavy industry.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] At the 20th Congress of the CPSU in 1956, a program for the formation of a single national economic complex of the Soviet Union was adopted.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] At the end of January 1957, a note from the First Secretary of the CPSU Central Committee Nikita Khrushchev on improving the management of industry and construction was sent to a wide circle of country leaders for discussion.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The essence of the note was a proposal to abolish departmental subordination of enterprises and transfer them to the regions.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Industry ministries were to be liquidated as unnecessary.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] It was assumed that such a reorganization would significantly increase the growth of industrial production, improve the quality of manufactured products, resources would be distributed more rationally, and the problems that the Soviet economy faced would be solved more quickly.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] One of the reasons for the appearance of the note on the need to decentralize management was the growing budget deficit of the Soviet Union: to cover foreign currency expenses, it was necessary to sell more and more gold abroad.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] According to Khrushchev, the existing centralization of management gave rise to "a number of abnormal phenomena", preventing society "from coming to a communist society, having such an excessively centralized system of economic management".
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] At the plenum of the Central Committee of the CPSU, which was held in February 1957, a discussion was held on the reform of the economic management system.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] However, Khrushchev's opinion prevailed, and at the session of the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union that followed the party plenum, a resolution was unanimously adopted on the creation of local councils of the national economy (sovnarkhozy, SNKH).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Before the reform, industry and construction were managed by sectoral ministries, which in 1957 were responsible for over 200,000 enterprises.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The beginning of the reform was marked by the abolition of 25 of the 37 union and union-republican ministries for industry and construction, and the transfer of the enterprises under their control to the direct subordination of economic councils.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The remaining ministries retained the "functions of planning the relevant branches of industry and ensuring a high technical level in the development of production".
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The same reorganization was carried out at the level of the republics of the Soviet Union.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] To implement the reform, 105 administrative economic regions were created in the Soviet Union, 70 of which were in the RSFSR.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Each such region had a national economy council with its own sectoral and functional departments and divisions, where economic management issues were resolved in relation to the given economic administrative region depending on its specialization.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] In March 1958, Khrushchev, while remaining the leader of the party, also took the post of head of the Soviet government, which, in the opinion of the country's leadership, should have contributed to the promotion of the reform of national economic management.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Decentralization of industrial management made it possible for the first time in Soviet public administration practice to bring management bodies as close as possible to the lowest management objects - industrial enterprises.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Thanks to this, the processes of planning, coordination, supply, construction, etc. were significantly accelerated.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The possibilities for inter-industry cooperation within the boundaries of a single administrative economic region expanded, which created the prerequisites for the formation of complex territorial production systems on the territory of economic regions.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Problems associated with the uneven regional economic development of the country also emerged.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] For this reason, less economically developed regions were doomed to chronically lag in the development of their territorial production complexes.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The first stage of the reform was accompanied by propaganda campaigns and slogans.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] In January 1959, at the 21st Congress of the CPSU, the "complete and final" victory of socialism in the Soviet union was declared and a Seven-year Plan for the development of the national economy for 1959-65 was approved.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The plan envisaged "catching up with and overtaking" the capitalist countries and bringing the Soviet economy to first place in the world in terms of production per capita.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] At the 22nd Congress of the CPSU, held in October 1961, a new, Third Program of the CPSU was presented - a program for building a communist society in the Soviet Union.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] In the area of economics, the program called for creating the material and technical base of communism within ten years (1961–71) through the electrification of the country, comprehensive mechanization and mass automation of production.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] It was supposed to increase the volume of industrial production by 6 times within 20 years, to double labour productivity within 10 years, and to double the level of labour productivity in the United States within 20 years.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Since the early 1960s, the gradual return of centralization to the economic management system, which was familiar to the party and economic nomenclature, began.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] First, economic councils of the union republics were created at the republican level - the Russian SSR, Ukrainian SSR and Kazakh SSR.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] To coordinate their activities, the Supreme Soviet of the National Economy was created in November 1962, and then the process of consolidating local economic councils began by merging economic administrative districts into larger economic districts.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] As a result of the consolidation, the number of such districts was reduced from 105 to 43.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The consolidation of economic councils caused a chain reaction of changes in other elements of the management system.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] In particular, the economic planning system was reorganized, as a result of which regional councils for the coordination and planning of production activities appeared at the local level.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Production collective and state farm administrations were also formed.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] By the mid-1960s, contrary to the originally planned program, the trend of centralized industry management of the country's economy actually gained the upper hand.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The reforms of the economic management bodies were accompanied by the reorganization of the administrative-territorial division of the Soviet Union and the restructuring of the activities of local party and soviet bodies.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] In November 1962, the plenum of the CPSU Central Committee decided to divide the party bodies into industrial and agricultural.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] It was assumed that such a division would improve party management of enterprises in the context of the territorial system of industrial management formed by the economic reform.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] By the mid-1960s, the management system had transformed from territorial to territorial-sectoral, which exacerbated its ineffectiveness.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The impotence of the economic councils to solve the economic problems of the Soviet Union became obvious.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] On October 14, 1964, Khrushchev, the main initiator and supporter of the reform, was removed from the leadership of the party and government with the wording "for health reasons".
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The participants in the plenum decided on the need to return to management of industry on the industry principle.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] A few days later, the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union issued a corresponding law, which provided for the abolition of the system of economic councils and the restoration of the management system through industry ministries.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The 1957 reform did not bring the desired results and ended with a return to a centralized system of industrial management.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The reform also failed to solve the problem of the growing expenditure of the country's gold reserves.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] In the period from 1953 to 1965, the Soviet government sold over 3 thousand tons of gold through Moscow Narodny Bank.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] If in 1953, 250-300 tons of gold were spent on purchasing food abroad, then in 1963–1964, when the reform gained full force, gold sales amounted to 1,244 tons.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The monetary reform carried out in 1961 led to the devaluation of the ruble.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] In 1962, there began to be interruptions in the supply of industrial goods and food products to populated areas.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The increase in retail prices for meat, meat products and butter, together with the deterioration of working conditions, caused a wave of strikes and workers' demonstrations in Krasnodar, Riga, Kyiv, Chelyabinsk, Leningrad, Omsk, Kemerovo, Donetsk, Artemyevsk, Kramatorsk.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The suppression of a workers' strike in Novocherkassk in 1962 was accompanied by the use of firearms and ended with the arrests and criminal prosecution of the strikers.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The growth rates of industry and agriculture continued to decline.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] A particularly sharp slowdown in growth was observed in the agriculture sector, where instead of the planned 70%, the growth of agricultural production by 1965 was only 15%.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The development of virgin lands turned the Soviet Union into a wheat exporter in the mid-1950s.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] However, droughts, dust storms, and the illiterate use of some lands in the southern regions, due to their peculiarities, led to a catastrophic drop in the productivity of virgin lands.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] After this, the leadership of the Soviet Union, for the first time in the history of the country, decided to purchase millions of tons of grain abroad.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] In 1963, 12.1 million tons of wheat were purchased abroad, in 1964 - 50 thousand tons of rice, in 1965 - 90 thousand tons of soybeans, which cost the state more than 1 billion US dollars.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] In general, the problem of shortages and quality of consumer goods was not solved.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] In 1962, only 5.3% of Soviet families had refrigerators (for comparison, in the USA - 98.3%).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] A positive result of the reform was the impressive quantitative economic indicators compared to economically developed countries.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] In particular, by 1965 the national income of the Soviet Union increased by 53% compared to 1958, production assets grew by 91%, and industrial production by 84%.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Real incomes of the population increased by one third.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Salaries and pensions for collective farmers were introduced.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] Due to the construction of buildings from large factory-made panels, the housing stock increased by 40%.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] In the period from 1950 to 1964, the area of housing increased by 2.3 times.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] The practical experience of territorial management of the economy was used to clarify and develop the theory of formation of territorial-production complexes, the foundations of which were laid by the Soviet economist Nikolay Kolosovsky.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] During the implementation of the reform, the systemic shortcomings of the Soviet economy and planning and management methods, which slowed down the growth of labour productivity in the national economy, were clearly revealed.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1957-soviet-economic-reform] This stimulated the all-Union economic discussion in 1962–1964, which in 1965 resulted in the Kosygin reform.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] About 80 percent of the city was destroyed.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] The earthquake, which measured 6.1 on the moment magnitude scale, occurred on July 26, 1963, at 04:17 UTC (5:17 am local time) in Skopje, Socialist Republic of Macedonia (present-day North Macedonia), then part of SFR Yugoslavia.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] The tremor lasted for 20 seconds and was felt mostly along the Vardar River Valley.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] There were also smaller aftershocks until 5:43.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] Following the earthquake, Josip Broz Tito, president of SFR Yugoslavia, sent a message of condolences to the Socialist Republic of Macedonia before visiting the city personally later on.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] Within a few days after the earthquake took place, 35 nations requested that the United Nations General Assembly place relief for Skopje on their list of agendas.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] The effort led to the implementation of a major urban and architectural reconstruction plan urban master-plan of Skopje 1963.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] Relief, in the form of money, medical, engineering and building teams and supplies was offered from 78 countries throughout the world.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] Kennedy ordered the Department of Defense and the Agency for International Development (USAID) to take actions for disaster assistance in Skopje by sending personnel, prefabricated houses, tent cities and other forms of relief.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] Substantial relief also arrived from the Soviet Union.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] Its leader, Nikita Khrushchev, visited Skopje personally.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] As the SFR Yugoslavia was a member of the Non-Aligned Movement during the Cold War, the American and Soviet troops stationed in Skopje could freely shake hands for the first time since their encounter on Elbe in 1945.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] The first foreign journalist who arrived in Skopje to report on the earthquake was David Binder of *The New York Times*.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] As he watched Skopje from the plane, he commented that the city looked like it was bombed.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] Dexion belongs to the Skopje's Municipality of Gjorče Petrov.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] At the same time, the UK Government made a gift of 44 x 24 feet wide Nissen huts which the Yugoslav authorities used as six schools to be used in satellite suburbs until permanent schools could be established.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] The construction of these huts was under the supervision of a small detachment of nine Royal Engineers led by Lt Charles Brodley RE.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] Later, "War on Want" purchased sufficient huts to provide accommodation for 2,000 workmen engaged in the reconstruction of the city and the Engineer detachment was increased to 49 under the command of Captain SL Rooth RE.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] In 1965, the Japanese architect Kenzo Tange was asked by the United Nations to enter a limited competition for the redevelopment of Skopje, after which Tange won 60% of the prize while the Yugoslav team won the remaining 40%.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] However, Tange's plan for Skopje (one of his major works) remains partly implemented, specifically concerning the New Skopje Railway Station and the so-called City Wall.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] As the city gradually began to recover, the need for revival of cultural life arose.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] The artist Pablo Picasso donated his painting Head of a Woman (1963), which was exhibited in the new post-earthquake Contemporary Art Museum of Macedonia.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] The museum building was a donation from Poland and was designed by several Polish architects.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] The concert hall "Univerzalna sala" was built with donations from around 35 countries and its prefabricated building was made in neighbouring Bulgaria.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] Several streets and objects in Skopje were named in honor of the countries which helped in their construction and/or donated housing.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] For example, the government of Romania donated the polyclinic medical center, which was named after its capital, Bucharest.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] In Karposh Municipality, there are Soviet-donated apartment buildings called in Macedonian: „руски згради“ (*ruski zgradi*, meaning "Russian buildings") and Swedish and Finnish prefabs called „шведски / фински бараки“ (*švedski* / *finski baraki*).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] One example is Skopje's Mexico Street (улица Мексичка, ulica Meksička).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] It was officially named in honor of Mexico and a memorial plaque from the Mexican president Adolfo López Mateos was unveiled at the location.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] In 2012, the street's well-known resident, the rock musician Vlatko Stefanovski and his brother, the playwright Goran Stefanovski protested against the mayor's decision to rename several city streets, including Mexico Street.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] The Stefanovski brothers reminded people that the street they grew up on and where the Macedonian rock group Leb i sol was formed was built with donations from Mexico and argued that this act of solidarity must never be forgotten.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] The old name *Meksička* was brought back in February 2021 by the Skopje City Council.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] Being rebuilt from ruins thanks to the relief from all around the world, Skopje is often referred to as "The City of International Solidarity", which is its motto.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] One year after the 1963 Skopje earthquake, the first Yugoslavian Code for Construction in Seismic Regions (temporary code 1964), was prepared by a committee consisting of international and national experts.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] The Skopje earthquake is referenced in many works of art including literature, music, theatre and films.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] An example is the Macedonian feature film *Memento*, directed by Dimitrie Osmanli in 1967.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1963-skopje-earthquake] An example from the field of literature is the poem *Skoplje 1963* by the Austrian poet Christine Busta.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The **1965 Soviet economic reform**, sometimes called the **Kosygin reform** (Russian: Косыгинская реформа) or **Liberman reform**, named after E.G.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Liberman, was a set of planned changes in the economy of the USSR.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] A centerpiece of these changes was the introduction of profitability and sales as the two key indicators of enterprise success.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Some of an enterprise's profits would go to three funds, used to reward workers and expand operations; most would go to the central budget.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The reforms were introduced politically by Alexei Kosygin—who had just become Premier of the Soviet Union following the removal of Nikita Khrushchev—and ratified by the Central Committee in September 1965.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] They reflected some long-simmering wishes of the USSR's mathematically-oriented economic planners, and initiated the shift towards increased decentralization in the process of economic planning.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The reforms, coinciding with the Eighth Five-Year Plan, led to continued growth of the Soviet economy.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The success of said reforms was short-lived, and with the events of Prague in 1968, fueled by Moscow's implementation of the reforms in Eastern Bloc countries, led to the reforms being curtailed.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Economists like Lev Gatovsky and Liberman were instrumental in framing the theoretical underpinnings of the Soviet economic reforms of the 1960s, advocating for the use of profit motives and market mechanisms within a socialist framework.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Under Lenin, the New Economic Policy had allowed and used the concepts of profit and incentives for regulation of the Soviet economy.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Stalin transformed this policy rapidly with the collectivization of farms and nationalization of industry, which was the result of the acceleration of central planning as exemplified by the "Five-Year Plans".
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Since about 1930, the Soviet Union had used a centralized system to manage its economy.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In this system, a single bureaucracy created economic plans, which assigned workers to jobs, set wages, dictated resource allocation, established the levels of trade with other countries, and planned the course of technological progress.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Retail prices for consumer goods were fixed at levels intended for market clearing.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The prices of wholesale goods were fixed, also, but these served an accounting function more than a market mechanism.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Collective farms also paid centrally determined prices for the supplies they needed, and unlike other sectors their workers received wages directly dependent on the profitability of the operation.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Although Soviet enterprises were theoretically governed by the principle of *khozraschet* (Russian: хозрасчёт, lit.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] 'business bookkeeping', or "accounting")—which required them to meet planners' expectations within the system of set prices for their inputs and outputs—they had little control over the biggest decisions affecting their operations.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Managers did have a responsibility to plan future gross output, which they chronically underestimated in order to later exceed the prediction.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The managers then received bonuses (*premia*) for surplus product regardless of whether it was produced in a cost-effective manner or whether their enterprise was profitable overall.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The bonuses for output came in amounts sometimes equal to the managers' base salaries.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The system also incentivized pointless increases in the size, weight, and cost of production outputs, simply because "more" had been produced.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The economic reforms emerged during a period of great ideological debate over economic planning.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] More mathematical, "cybernetic", viewpoints were at first considered deviant from orthodox Marxist economics, which considered the value of goods to derive strictly from labor.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] This doctrine, elaborated in such works as Stalin's 1952 book, *Economic Problems of Socialism in the USSR*, described the price system as a capitalist relic which would eventually disappear from communist society.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Nevertheless, computerized economics gained an important role for top planners, even while conventional Marxist–Leninist political economy was taught in most schools and promoted for public consumption.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The rising influence of statistical planning in the Soviet economy was reflected in the creation of the Central Economic Mathematical Institute (Центральный экономико-математический институт; TSEMI), led by Vasily Sergeevich Nemchinov.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Nemchinov, along with linear programming inventor Leonid Kantorovich and investment analyst Viktor Valentinovich Novozhilov, received the Lenin Prize in 1965.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The battle between "optimal" planning and convention planning raged throughout the 1960s.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Another tendency in economic planning emphasized "normative value of processing", or the importance of needs and wants in evaluating the value of production.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Major changes throughout the Soviet world became possible in 1964 with the ousting of Nikita Khrushchev and the rise of Alexei Kosygin and Leonid Brezhnev.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Economic policy was a significant area of retrospective anti-Khrushchev criticism in the Soviet press.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] This 'reformist' economic tendency in the Soviet Union had corollaries and some mutual reinforcement in Eastern Europe.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Kosygin criticized the inefficiency and inertia of economic policy under the previous administration.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] He presented a plan, including the ideas expressed by Liberman and Nemchinov, to the Communist Party Central Committee Plenum in September 1965.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The Central Committee's acceptance of the plan became crucial for practical implementation of theoretical ideas.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] According to official rationale for the reform, the increasing complexity of economic relations reduced the efficacy of economic planning and therefore reduced economic growth.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] It was recognized that the existing system of planning did not motivate enterprises to reach high rates of production or to introduce organizational or technical innovations.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Given more freedom to deviate publicly from party orthodoxy, newspapers offered new proposals for the Soviet economy.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Antonov published an article in *Izvestia* on November 22, 1961, with the title "For All and For Oneself"—advocating more power for enterprise directors.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] A widely publicized economic rationale for reform came from Evsei Liberman of the Kharkov Institute of Engineering and Economics.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] An article by Liberman on this topic, titled "Plans, Profits, and Bonuses" appeared in *Pravda* in September 1962.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Liberman, influenced by the economic "optimizers", argued for the (re)introduction of profitability as a core economic indicator.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These proposals were controversial, and criticized especially as regressions towards a capitalist economic system.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Critics also argued that reliance on profitability would skew the proportions in which different goods were produced.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Unlike Liberman in 1962, Trapeznikov suggested that the need for reform had been embraced by party decisionmakers and would soon become a reality.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In the following month, *Pravda* published six more articles from academicians, planners, and managers advocating reform.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Several economic experiments were initiated to test Liberman's proposals.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These began in 1964 with new policies for two garment factories: the Bolshevichka in Moscow and the Mayak in Gorky.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] When operations at the garment factories proved tolerably successful, the experiment was expanded to about 400 other enterprises, mostly in large cities.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] One experiment in Lviv involved a coal mine and factories producing clothing, shoes, and heavy lifting equipment.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The coal mine, in particular, reportedly became more profitable after shifting to a system using bonuses and more independent decisionmaking.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Some of the experimental plants ran into problems, however, due to the unreliability of suppliers continuing to operate on the old system.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The Mayak plant faced a dilemma in trying to implement the centrally mandated experimental reforms, while simultaneously receiving contradictory orders from the local *sovnarkhoz* (regional council).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The reform was administered by the Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union and the Council of Ministers.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The number of policy targets was reduced from 30 to 9 (the rest remained indicators).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Enterprises were required to determine the detailed range and variety of products, using their own funds to invest in production, establish long-term contractual arrangements with suppliers and customers and to determine the number of personnel.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Key importance was attributed to the integral indicators of economic efficiency of production — profits and profitability.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] There was the opportunity to create a number of funds based on the expense of profits — funds for the development of production, material incentives, housing, etc.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The enterprise was allowed to use the funds at its discretion.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Pricing: Wholesale sales prices would be recalibrated to reflect costs and encourage economic efficiency.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The most important changes resulting from the Liberman/Kosygin reforms involved the role of profit in the Soviet economic system.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] *Rentabelnost'* ("profitability", Russian: рентабельность) and *realizatsiya* ("sales", Russian: реализация) became the twin success indicators for enterprises.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] *Rentabelnost'* was defined in terms of the *ratio* between profits and capital, while *realizatsiya* (also meaning "implementation") depended on the total volume of sales.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Success by these measurements led to the allocation of money to a fund, which could be disbursed according to a pre-defined sequence.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The funds first went to pay for capital—including interest paid to *Gosbank*, the State Bank.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Then, they went to the new incentive funds.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Finally, they could be used by an enterprise to expand its capital for operations.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Any profit extending above the maximum for spending would go to the central budget.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The production development fund (PDF): A 'development' fund for the overall organization.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Formerly, bonuses had come from the same fund as wages.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Now, enterprise managers had slightly more discretion over how to allocate them.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] They could move some amounts of money between the bonus fund and the social welfare fund.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] They also had more power to influence wages by classifying different workers.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In practice, the bonuses had the greatest impact on the payment of elite personnel (technicians and "employees" as opposed to "workers"), thereby counteracting the effect of Khrushchev-era wage reforms.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] An experimental system introduced at some enterprises offered extra bonuses for specific achievements—not just as a portion of total profits.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] For example, engineers using fuel more efficiently (during a shortage) could receive large premia calculated as a percentage of the money they saved.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Along with more direct responsibility for the wage fund, enterprises also gained the power to fire workers.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In fact, the reform gave new incentive for layoffs, which in some cases could increase profitability.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] (When these occurred, the workers did not have a 'social safety net' in place in the form of unemployment insurance and career assistance).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] To encourage accurate planning, enterprises now would be punished for performing below *or above* their planned goals.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Enterprises would also pay rent for land and natural resources.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The rationale for this practice was economic optimization.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] For example, land of differing quality required different inputs of manpower to achieve the same outputs, and thus should factor differently into the budget of an enterprise.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Bank loans, to be repaid later with interest, would be used to fund more investment projects—to incentive the careful use of funds and the speedy creation of profit.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Five different interest rates would be set, ranging from preferential to normal to punitive.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] An additional capital charge—i.e., tax—would be assessed for each enterprise based on the capital it retained: working capital, equipment, and surplus stocks.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Enterprises were to submit annual plans, called *tekhpromfinplans (from Russian: техпромфинплан (ru:Техпрофинплан) - technical and financial production plan)*, stipulating production plans by quarter and month.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Higher-ups would then approve these plans (or not) and allocate supplies and money.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The enterprise then sells its products, within the constraints of the plan.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] It is empowered to reject or return (within ten days) unneeded inputs to the supplier.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The key change which represented "decentralization" was the delegation of responsibility over modernization investments.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] However, modernization plans remained subject to central approval, as well as approval from the bank which lent the money.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The amount of development expected under these auspices fell far short of expectations, as the necessary labour and materials were simply undersupplied.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] One response to this problem in 1969 was to shift more incentives to the contractors.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] For the "optimal planners" this limited decentralization was inadequate, and the new importance assigned to "profit" was incomplete because enterprises did not control enough of the factors which might affect it.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These councils spelled the end of a short-lived phase of worker control over production, which the Bolsheviks regarded as inefficient.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Under the New Economic Policy beginning in 1921, enterprises were classified based on their relative interdependence (and necessity to war production) or autonomy (i.e. those "endowed with complete financial and commercial independence").
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The many enterprises in the latter category were not nationalized, but instead placed under the guidance of the VSNKh, with the plan to group them into "trusts" based on production chains or geographic proximity.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] This model underwent various reorganizations, including the strengthening of *edinonachalie*, control of production units by a single manager.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These single managers at times controlled a wide range of production activities within a single area.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The economic reform of 1957 reintroduced the *sovnarkhozy*, 104 in number, to govern production by region.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Where applicable, these corresponded closely with the boundaries of the *oblasty* (political jurisdictions).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Complaints immediately arose that these councils did not optimize overall production chains, due to their regional focus, and that they conflicted with the authority of *Gosplan*.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In 1962, the 104 *sovnarkhozy* were consolidated into 47 larger jurisdictions (one of which controlled all of Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, Tadzhikistan, and Kirgizia).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] However, by 1962–1963, the *sovnarkhozy* were becoming subordinate to numerous other agencies and organizations.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Gosplan was to be stripped of its planning authority in favor of a revitalized VSNKh.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Kosygin took aim at these "outdated forms of management" and included in his 1965 speech a return to ministries as core administrators.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] His plan resembled the ministry system under Stalin, but with a smaller number: nine all-Union ministries organized by industry (e.g., Ministry of Light Industry, Ministry of the Radio Industry, Ministry of the Chemical Industry) and eleven supervising operations within each union-republic.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The latter regional agencies reported both to the local council and to the central ministry with jurisdiction over their production type.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Gosplan had the responsibility for creating annual and long-term plans, and for guiding development and resource management.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] *Gossnab* became the primary coordinator of material-technical supply, and was charged with large-scale analysis (possibly using computers) to increase supply chain efficiency.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The 1965 reforms somewhat altered the role of the Party in economic administration.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Local officials were to oversee operations from a distance to ensure compliance with the spirit of the reforms.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The plan called for more detailed and scientific central planning, including annual targets.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These plans would be calculated using computer systems.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Distribution of supplies and products would take place in different ways.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Central planners would allocate certain scarce and vital goods.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] For others, enterprises could form "direct ties" within which they developed a contractual exchange relationship.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The authors of the reforms knew from the outset that changes would take effect gradually, based on the careful writing of plans through the years 1966 and 1967.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The first 43 enterprises, along with several "experiments" for which planning began before the September 1965 Plenum, shifted to the new model at the beginning of 1966.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Transfer of another 180–200 was accomplished in early 1966.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These were already profitable, well-positioned businesses, and reflected well on the reform in early evaluations.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] On July 1, 1966, 430 more enterprises were transferred; these included some large operations and themselves constituted 12% of total production.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] By the end of 1966, more than 704 enterprises had switched.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The Eighth Five-Year Plan would have instantiated some of the proposed reforms.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] (The Five-Year Plan dealt with a broad range of issues, with more of a focus on people's overall living conditions.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Most light industry was to transfer at the beginning of 1967.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The remaining enterprises to switch over in two stages, taking effect on July 1, 1967, and January 1, 1968.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The complete transfer of all enterprises proceeded steadily, if not exactly on schedule.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] By April 1, 1967, 2,500 enterprises, responsible for 20% of output, had switched.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] By the end of the year, 7,000 industrial enterprises (out of 45,000), 1,500 trucking firms (out of 4,100), and all 25 railroad systems had transferred.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Together these made up the backbone of Soviet industry.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] They were followed by smaller enterprises: 11,000 more in 1968.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The plan met with considerable initial confusion from enterprise managers who, throughout their careers, had underestimated their potential output in order to later exceed their quota.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Also difficult was the requirement to comply with the new directives before all aspects of the economy (i.e., prices, resource availability) had shifted over.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] And the reluctance of certain bureaucrats to comply with the new policies was the subject of sustained criticism in the press, including multiple editorials by Liberman himself.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In April 1966, for example, Liberman recommended creating a "brain trust of the reconstruction" which could veto counter-reformist policies in the bureaucracy.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Officials at the higher administrative levels (i.e., the ministries), continued to issue orders at odds with the profitability plans of the enterprise managers.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Some traditional problems—such as accumulation (which undercut profitability) of surplus valuable supplies, lest they be needed later in a time of shortage—persisted.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Gossnab and the ministries were blamed for failing to make the appropriate inputs available to the enterprises.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] A price revision, the first since 1955, was announced in mid-1966, apparently following some non-trivial internal disputes.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The revision called for moderate re-alignment of prices, to conform more with production costs, and went into effect in July 1967.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Wholesale fuel and ore prices increased substantially.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Prices on consumer goods did not officially increase at all; yet consumers paid higher prices for things they wanted and needed, since newer, more expensive goods were introduced to the market, and the old versions withdrawn.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Many enterprises were encouraged to sell or give away excess equipment, since all available capital was factored into the calculation of productivity.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Certain measurements of efficiency improved.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These included rising sales per rouble worth of capital and falling wages per rouble of sales.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The enterprises rendered large portions of their profits, sometimes 80%, to the central budget.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These payments of "free" remaining profits substantially exceeded capital charges.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] However, central planners were not satisfied with the impact of the reform.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In particular, they observed that wages had increased without a commensurate rise in productivity.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Many of the specific changes were revised or reversed in 1969–1971.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The reforms somewhat reduced the role of the Party in micromanaging economic operations.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The backlash against economic reformism joined with opposition to political liberalization to trigger the full-blown invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Soviet officials and press nevertheless continued to advance the idea of the 1965 reform.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Numerous **Cyrillic alphabets** are based on the Cyrillic script.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The early Cyrillic alphabet was developed in the 9th century AD and replaced the earlier Glagolitic script developed by the theologians Cyril and Methodius.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] It is the basis of alphabets used in various languages, past and present, Slavic origin, and non-Slavic languages influenced by Russian.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] As of 2011, around 252 million people in Eurasia use it as the official alphabet for their national languages.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Cyrillic is one of the most-used writing systems in the world.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The creator is Saint Clement of Ohrid from the Preslav literary school in the First Bulgarian Empire.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Some of these are illustrated below; for others, and for more detail, see the links.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] While these languages largely have phonemic orthographies, there are occasional exceptions—for example, Russian ⟨г⟩ is pronounced /v/ in a number of words, an orthographic relic from when they were pronounced /ɡ/ (e.g. его *yego* 'him/his', is pronounced [jɪˈvo] rather than [jɪˈɡo]).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Spellings of names transliterated into the Roman alphabet may vary, especially й (*y*/*j*/*i*), but also г (*gh*/*g*/*h*) and ж (*zh*/*j*).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] However, in some alphabets invented in the 19th century, such as Chuvash, umlauts and breves also were used.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Bulgarian and Bosnian Sephardim without Hebrew typefaces occasionally printed Judeo-Spanish in Cyrillic.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Non-Slavic alphabets are generally modelled after Russian, but often bear striking differences, particularly when adapted for Caucasian languages.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The first few of these alphabets were developed by Orthodox missionaries for the Finnic and Turkic peoples of Idel-Ural (Mari, Udmurt, Mordva, Chuvash, and Kerashen Tatars) in the 1870s.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Later, such alphabets were created for some of the Siberian and Caucasus peoples who had recently converted to Christianity.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] In the 1930s, some of those languages were switched to the New Turkic Alphabet.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Abkhazian and Ossetian languages were switched to the Mkhedruli script, but after the death of Joseph Stalin, both also adopted Cyrillic.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The last language to adopt Cyrillic was the Gagauz language, which had used Greek script before.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] In Uzbekistan, Azerbaijan and Turkmenistan, the use of Cyrillic to write local languages has often been a politically controversial issue since the collapse of the Soviet Union, as it evokes the era of Soviet rule and Russification.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Some of Russia's peoples such as the Tatars have also tried to drop Cyrillic, but the move was halted under Russian law.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] A number of languages have switched from Cyrillic to either a Roman-based orthography or a return to a former script.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Cyrillic alphabets continue to be used in several Slavic (Russian, Ukrainian, Serbian, Bulgarian, Macedonian, Belarusian) and non-Slavic (Kazakh, Uzbek, Kyrgyz, Tajik, Gagauz, Mongolian) languages.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The following table lists the Cyrillic letters which are used in the alphabets of most of the national languages which use a Cyrillic alphabet.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Exceptions and additions for particular languages are noted below.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The soft sign ⟨ь⟩ usually does not represent a sound, but modifies the sound of the preceding letter, indicating palatalization ("softening"), also separates the consonant and the following vowel.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Sometimes it does not have phonetic meaning, just orthographic; e.g.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Russian туш, **tush** [tuʂ] 'flourish after a toast'; тушь, **tushʹ** [tuʂ] 'India ink'.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] In some languages, a hard sign ⟨ъ⟩ or apostrophe ⟨’⟩ just separates the consonant and the following vowel (бя [bʲa], бья [bʲja], бъя = б’я [bja]).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Cyrillic alphabet was originally developed in the First Bulgarian Empire during the 9th – 10th century AD at the Preslav Literary School.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Cyrillic alphabet was used in the then much bigger territory of Bulgaria (including most of today's Serbia), North Macedonia, Kosovo, Albania, Northern Greece (Macedonia region), Romania and Moldova, officially from 893.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] It was also transferred from Bulgaria and adopted by the East Slavic languages in Kievan Rus' and evolved into the Russian alphabet and the alphabets of many other Slavic (and later non-Slavic) languages.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Later, some Slavs modified it and added/excluded letters from it to better suit the needs of their own language varieties.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] South Slavic Cyrillic alphabets (with the exception of Bulgarian) are generally derived from Serbian Cyrillic.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] It, and by extension its descendants, differs from the East Slavic ones in that the alphabet has generally been simplified: Letters such as Й, Я, Ю, and Щ representing /j/, /ja/, /ju/, and /ɕ(ː)/ in Russian, respectively, have been removed.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Instead, these are represented by the letter ⟨Ј⟩ and digraphs ⟨ја⟩, ⟨ју⟩, and ⟨шч/шт⟩, respectively.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Additionally, the letter Е, representing /je/ in Russian, is instead pronounced /e/ or /ɛ/, with /je/ being represented by ⟨је⟩.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Alphabets based on the Serbian that add new letters often do so by adding an acute accent ⟨´⟩ over an existing letter.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Ćiro Truhelka claimed Serbo-Croatian language briefly used the Cyrillic script in areas with large Croatian or Bosnian speaking populations.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Bosniak scholars call it *Bosnian Script*.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Serb scholars call it *Serbian script*, as part of variant of Serbian Cyrillic and deem the term "bosančica" Anti-Serb Austro-Hungarian propaganda.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Croat scholars call it *Croatian Cyrillic*.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] When an iotated vowel (vowel whose sound begins with [j]) follows a consonant, the consonant is palatalized.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The hard sign indicates that this does not happen, and the [j] sound will appear only in front of the vowel.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The soft sign indicates that the consonant should be palatalized in addition to a [j] preceding the vowel.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The soft sign also indicates that a consonant before another consonant or at the end of a word is palatalized.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Before 1918, there were four extra letters in use: Іі (replaced by Ии), Ѳѳ (Фита "Fita", replaced by Фф), Ѣѣ (Ять "Yat", replaced by Ее), and Ѵѵ (ижица "Izhitsa", replaced by Ии); these were eliminated by reforms of Russian orthography.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Carpathian Rusyn language is spoken by the Carpatho-Rusyns in Carpathian Ruthenia, Slovakia, and Poland.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Carpathian Rusyn alphabet differs from Ukrainian in that the letters Ё, Ы, and the hard sign (Ъ), from Russian, are also used, and the order is slightly different.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Pannonian Rusyn language is spoken by the Pannonian Rusyns.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] This alphabet uses all the letters of the Ukrainian alphabet except Dotted I (І і).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Note that Pannonian Rusyn is a West Slavic language despite its name.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Romanian language used the Cyrillic script up to the 19th century (see Romanian Cyrillic alphabet).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Nowadays, this alphabet is still official in the unrecognized republic of Transnistria (see Moldovan Cyrillic alphabet).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Ladino uses the Cyrillic script in occasional Bulgarian Sephardic publications.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Romani is written in Cyrillic in Serbia, Montenegro, Bulgaria and the former USSR.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Ossetic language has officially used the Cyrillic script since 1937.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Tajik alphabet is written using a Cyrillic-based alphabet.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Karelian language was written in the Cyrillic script in various forms until 1940 when publication in Karelian ceased in favor of Finnish, except for Tver Karelian, written in a Latin alphabet.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] In 1989 publication began again in the other Karelian dialects and Latin alphabets were used, in some cases with the addition of Cyrillic letters such as ь.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Over the last century, the alphabet used to write Kildin Sámi has changed three times: from Cyrillic to Latin and back again to Cyrillic.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Work on the latest version of the official orthography commenced in 1979.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] It was officially approved in 1982 and started to be widely used by 1987.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Cyrillic script was used for the Bashkir language after the winter of 1938.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Cyrillic alphabet is used for the Chuvash language since the late 19th century, with some changes in 1938.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Cyrillic letters Бб, Гг, Дд, Ёё, Жж, Зз, Оо, Фф, Цц, Щщ and Ъъ are not used in native Chuvash words, but only for Russian loans.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Kazakh can be alternatively written in the Latin alphabet.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Latin is expected to entirely replace Cyrillic by the 2030s, alongside the modified Arabic alphabet (in the People's Republic of China, Iran and Afghanistan).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Cyrillic letters Вв, Ёё, Цц, Чч, Ъъ, Ьь and Ээ are not used in native Kazakh words, but only for Russian loans.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Kyrgyz has also been written in Latin and in Arabic.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Tatar has used Cyrillic since 1939, but the Russian Orthodox Tatar community has used Cyrillic since the 19th century.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] In 2000 a new Latin alphabet was adopted for Tatar, but it is used generally on the Internet.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Cyrillic letters Ёё, Цц, Щщ are not used in native Tatar words, but only for Russian loans.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Turkmen, written 1940–1994 exclusively in Cyrillic, since 1994 officially in Roman, but in everyday communication Cyrillic is still used along with Roman script.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] From 1941 the Cyrillic script was used exclusively.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] In 1998 the government has adopted a Latin alphabet to replace it.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The deadline for making this transition has however been repeatedly changed, and Cyrillic is still more common.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] It is not clear that the transition will be made at all.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] In addition to the letters from the Russian alphabet, А–Я, except for Щ and Ы, the Uzbek Cyrillic alphabet includes Ў, Қ, Ғ and Ҳ at the end.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] They are distinct letters in the Uzbek Cyrillic alphabet and are sorted after Я as shown above.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Several Cyrillic alphabets have been used to write Yakut, but the current alphabet was adopted in 1939.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Letters in **Bold** are only used in Russian Loanwords.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Living Northwest Caucasian languages are generally written using Cyrillic alphabets.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Abaza is a Caucasian language, spoken by Abazins in the Karachay-Cherkessia Republic, Russia.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Abkhaz is a Caucasian language, spoken in the Autonomous Republic of Abkhazia, Georgia.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Adyghe is a Caucasian language, spoken in the Republic of Adygea, Russia.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Kabardian is a Caucasian language, spoken in the Republics of Kabardino-Balkaria and Karachay-Cherkessia, Russia.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Northeast Caucasian languages are generally written using Cyrillic alphabets.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Avar is a Caucasian language, spoken in the Republic of Dagestan, of the Russian Federation, where it is co-official together with other Caucasian languages like Dargwa, Lak, Lezgian and Tabassaran.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] All these alphabets, and other ones (Abaza, Adyghe, Chechen, Ingush, Kabardian) have an extra sign: palochka (Ӏ), which gives voiceless occlusive consonants its particular ejective sound.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Lezgian is spoken by the Lezgins, who live in southern Dagestan and northern Azerbaijan.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Lezgian is a literary language and an official language of Dagestan.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Mongolic languages include Khalkha (in Mongolia; Cyrillic is official since 1941, in practice from 1946), Buryat (around Lake Baikal; Cyrillic is used since the 1930s) and Kalmyk (northwest of the Caspian Sea; Cyrillic is used in various forms since the 1920-30s).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Khalkha Mongolian is also written with the Mongol vertical alphabet, which was the official script before 1941.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Since the beginning of the 1990s Mongolia has been making attempts to extend the rather limited use of Mongol script and the most recent National Plan for Mongol Script aims to bring its use to the same level as Cyrillic by 2025 and maintain a dual-script system (digraphia).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] This table contains all the characters used.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Long vowels are indicated with double letters.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Cyrillic letters Кк, Пп, Фф and Щщ are not used in native Mongolian words, but only for Russian or other loans (Пп may occur in native onomatopoeic words).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Buryat (буряад) Cyrillic script is similar to the Khalkha above, but Ьь indicates palatalization as in Russian.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Buryat does not use Вв, Кк, Пп, Фф, Цц, Чч, Щщ or Ъъ in its native words (Пп may occur in native onomatopoeic words).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The Kalmyk (хальмг) Cyrillic script differs from Khalkha in some respects: there are additional letters (Әә, Җҗ, Ңң, Һһ), letters Ээ, Юю and Яя appear only word-initially, long vowels are written double in the first syllable (нөөрин), but single in syllables after the first.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] Short vowels are omitted altogether in syllables after the first syllable (хальмг = /xaʎmaɡ/). Жж and Пп are used in loanwords only (Russian, Tibetan, etc.), but Пп may occur in native onomatopoeic words.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/cyrillic-alphabets-p01] The letters Ӷ ӷ, Ӄ ӄ, Ӈ ӈ, Ӽ ӽ are sometimes replaced by Гʼ гʼ, Кʼ кʼ, Нʼ нʼ, Хʼ хʼ or Ґ ґ, Қ қ, Ң ң, Ҳ ҳ.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] After 1989 a set of new internet domains was created in Europe, including .pl (Poland), .cs (Czechoslovakia), .yu (Yugoslavia) and .dd (East Germany).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] Among them, there was also a domain for the USSR – .su.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] Initially, before two-letter ccTLDs became standard, the Soviet Union was to receive a .ussr domain.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] The .su domain was proposed by the 19-year-old Finnish student Petri Ojala.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] On 26 December 1991 the country was dissolved and its constituent republics gained independence, which should have caused the domain to begin a phase-out process, as happened with those of East Germany, Czechoslovakia, and Yugoslavia.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] Until 1994 there was no assigned top-level domain name for Russia.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] For this reason the country continued to use the Soviet domain.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] In 1994, the .ru domain was created, which was supposed to eventually replace the .su domain (domains for the republics other than Russia were created at different times in the mid-nineties).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] The domain was supposed to be withdrawn by ICANN, but it was kept at the request of the Russian government and Internet users.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] In 2001, the managers of the domain stated that they would commence accepting new .su registrations, but it is unclear whether this action was compatible with ICANN policies.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] In September 2007, lobbyists stated that they had started negotiations with ICANN on retaining the domain.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] In March 2025, ICANN reportedly notified the operator of the domain, the Russian Institute for Development of Public Networks (ROSNIIROS), of a planned phase-out of the domain by 2030.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] As of May 2026, the .su ccTLD contained over 112,000 domains.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] From September 2026, Rucenter added a new mandatory identity registration requirement in response to new Russian regulation (Federal Law No.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] This affects all of Rucenter's managed domains including .ru, .su, and .рф, requiring all existing and new registrations to submit identity information to the **Gosuslugi**/**ESIA** portal, the Unified Identification and Authentication System.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] This verification system requires cooperation with the registrar, and many registrars had not updated their systems to permit verification for registrants, meaning that on September 1 of 2026 a large amount of .su domains will have renewals fail and the total number of domains is likely to drop.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] The domain was intended to be used by Soviet institutions and companies operating in the USSR.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] The dissolution of the Soviet Union a mere 15 months after the establishment of .su meant that the new TLD was superseded by the new country TLDs of the former Soviet republics.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] Most of the .su domains are registered in Russia and the United States.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] According to data from May 2025, there were over 111,500 registered domains with the .su TLD (there are over 5.895 million .ru domains).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] Some organizations with roots in the former Soviet Union also still use this TLD.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] The pro-Russian Ukrainian separatist Donetsk People's Republic have also registered their domain with the TLD.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] The .su domain, along with .ru briefly hosted white supremacist websites that had been deplatformed elsewhere, including *The Daily Stormer*.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] Following complaints from Russia's internet regulator Roskomnadzor however, such websites have been removed from both TLDs.
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] The domain also hosted many cybercrime activities until 2013 due to the relaxed and outdated terms of use, along with staying out of focus (2% usage comparing to the primary .ru zone).
[src:cyrillic-alphabets/su] Rules for timely suspension of malicious domains have been in place since 2013 in response to the issue.
